[normal]Written evidence submitted by the Combined Heat and Power Association (HOT50)[bold]The Combined Heat and Power Association (CHPA) welcomes
[normal] the opportunity to provide written evidence to the Energy and Climate Change Committee’s inquiry on heat. 
[normal]The 
[normal]CHPA
[normal] is the leading advocate 
[normal]of 
[normal]an integrated approach to delivering energy services using combined heat and power and district heating and cooli
[normal]ng.
[normal] 
[normal]The CHPA’s response sets out key elements of 
[normal]the 
[normal]heat 
[normal]sector 
[normal]and highlights immediate issues where policy focus would be of value. 
[normal]We 
[normal]would also welcome the opportunity to provide oral evidence to the Committee. 
[normal]Accounting for half of 
[normal]UK
[normal] energy demand, h
[normal]eat is central to the energy debate
[normal]. 
[normal]If we are t
[normal]o achieve our decarbonisation 
[normal]commitments
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]reducing emissions from heat 
[normal]must 
[normal]be at the heart of energy policy.
[normal] 
[normal]DECC’s creatio
[normal]n of a heat directorate in 2011, and the publication of 
[normal]H
[normal]eat 
[normal]S
[normal]trateg
[normal]ies
[normal] 
[normal]in 
[normal]201
[normal]2 and 201
[normal]3 
[normal]demonstrates 
[normal]Government
[normal]’s growing
[normal] 
[normal]recogni
[normal]tion
[normal] 
[normal]of 
[normal]the importance of heat
[normal]. 
[normal]Heat policy [bold]must focus on the needs of the consumer[bold]While p
[normal]ower is a standardised commodity
[normal],
[normal] heat is highly 
[normal]specific 
[normal]to the consumer
[normal]’s requirements
[normal]. 
[normal]For example, h
[normal]omes
[normal] and offices 
[normal]need low-temperature heat for heating and hot water
[normal], while
[normal] 
[normal]i
[normal]ndustries need high temperature heat for industrial processes. 
[normal]The difficulty 
[normal]of transporting 
[normal]heat 
[normal]over long
[normal] distances ensures heat generation is always 
[normal]generated 
[normal]local
[normal]ly
[normal] and
[normal], therefore,
[normal] 
[normal]involves a close relationship with the final 
[normal]user
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]H
[normal]eat 
[normal]policy
[normal], therefore,
[normal] requires
[normal] a more
[normal] decentralised
[normal] and
[normal] 
[normal]user
[normal]-orientated 
[normal]approach
[normal]. 
[normal]With 
[normal]such an 
[normal]approach, it becomes clear that there 
[normal]is no 
[normal]one 
[normal]solution for decarbonising 
[normal]UK
[normal] 
[normal]heat
[normal]. Rather 
[normal]a
[normal] 
[normal]suite of technologies 
[normal]is needed
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]each
[normal] tailored to 
[normal]specific users’ 
[normal]needs.
[normal] 
[normal]An integrated systems approach controls costs for consumers[bold]With an increased use of elec
[normal]tricity for energy needs, including heat and transport, there is a pressing need to consider how different energy needs interact. 
[normal]The 2013 Heat Strategy recognises the 
[normal]energy system’s 
[normal]complex nature and recognises that a more cost-effective system will ari
[normal]se when all energy uses are better integrated.
[normal] 
[normal]By using tools such as thermal
[normal] 
[normal]stores, a more integrated energy system 
[normal]can 
[normal]help reduce overall costs by better managing electricity demand and supply
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Without considering heat and power 
[normal]together
[normal], the UK risks
[normal] creating a very expensive, inefficient energy system.
[normal]Energy efficiency links key [bold]options [bold]for decarbonising[bold] heat[bold]T
[normal]here are many technologies
[normal] 
[normal]which
[normal] can offer low carbon heat 
[normal]including generation technologies like 
[normal]heat pumps, solar
[normal] thermal
[normal], 
[normal]combined heat 
[normal]and power (
[normal]CHP
[normal])
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]However, w
[normal]hatever generation solution is deployed, energy efficiency 
[normal]across generation, delivery 
[normal]infrastructure, 
[normal]and final demand
[normal] is key
[normal]. 
[normal]Currently,
[normal] 
[normal]t
[normal]he high temperatures required by 
[normal]industrial 
[normal]processes 
[normal]are
[normal] 
[normal]mostly 
[normal]provid
[normal]ed by individual gas-fired boilers
[normal] or CHP
[normal], but with an increasing role for bio
[normal]energy
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]he relatively high cost of electricity makes it 
[normal]prohibitively 
[normal]expensive
[normal] 
[normal]for widespread 
[normal]industrial 
[normal]heat generation
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Electrically
[normal]-generated heat 
[normal]is 
[normal]needed for some 
[normal]processes such as iron and 
[normal]aluminium
[normal] smelting
[normal] where the high temperatures required cannot be 
[normal]readily 
[normal]achieved by other means
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Energy efficiency sits at the heart of industrial heat[bold] [bold]decarbonisation[bold] [bold]F
[normal]or medium temperature industrial heat needs, fossil and 
[normal]bioenergy
[normal] will remain the key sources for cost-effective heat
[normal] in the medium term
[normal]. 
